solutions.content:
# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
the function scans the vector, identifies the positions where zeros need to be duplicated, shifts the elements accordingly, and inserts the duplicated zeros in the correct positions.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Initialization of variables:

pos is initialized to 0, representing the position in the arr vector.
ptr is initialized to 0, representing the index in the for loop.
First for loop:

It iterates over the elements of the arr vector using the index i.
It also keeps track of the number of iterations in the ct variable.
Inside the loop, it checks if the current element at index ct is equal to 0.
If it is 0, it increments i by 1 to skip the next element.
Otherwise, it updates pos to the current value of ct and ptr to the current value of i.
Second for loop:

It iterates backward starting from ptr and continues until index 0.
Inside the loop, it assigns the value at index pos to the current element at index i.
If the value at index pos is 0 and i is not 0, it decrements i by 1 and assigns 0 to the previous index.
It then decrements pos to move to the previous element.
Third for loop:

It iterates over the elements of the arr vector starting from index ptr + 1.
Inside the loop, it assigns 0 to each element.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of the duplicateZeros function can be analyzed as follows:

The first for loop iterates over the elements of the arr vector once, so its time complexity is O(n), where n is the size of the vector.

The second for loop iterates backward from ptr to 0, which can have at most n iterations. Therefore, its time complexity is O(n).

The third for loop iterates over the elements from ptr + 1 to the end of the arr vector, which also has at most n iterations. Thus, its time complexity is O(n).

As a result, the overall time complexity of the function is O(n), where n is the size of the input vector arr.

- Space complexity:O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Regarding space complexity, the function does not use any additional data structures that grow with the input size. It only uses a constant amount of extra space for the variables pos and ptr. Therefore, the space complexity of the function is O(1), indicating constant space usage.

# Code
``` C++ []
class Solution {
public:
    void duplicateZeros(vector<int>& arr) {
        int pos = 0;  // Variable to track the position of the last non-zero element
        int ptr = 0;  // Variable to track the current index in the for loop

        // First loop: Find positions for duplicating zeros and update `pos` and `ptr`
        for (int i = 0, ct = 0; i < arr.size(); i++, ct++) {
            if (arr[ct] == 0) {
                i++;  // Increment `i` to skip the next element when a zero is encountered
            } else {
                pos = ct;  // Update `pos` with the index of the last non-zero element
                ptr = i;   // Update `ptr` with the current index in the for loop
            }
        }

        // Second loop: Perform duplication and shifting
        for (int i = ptr; i >= 0; i--) {
            arr[i] = arr[pos];  // Shift the elements to the right by assigning the value of the last non-zero element

            // Duplicate zeros by inserting 0 in the correct position
            if (arr[pos] == 0 && i != 0) {
                arr[--i] = 0;  // Decrement `i` and assign 0 to the previous index
            }

            pos--;  // Move to the previous non-zero element
        }

        // Third loop: Set remaining elements to 0
        for (int i = ptr + 1; i < arr.size(); i++) {
            arr[i] = 0;  // Set the remaining elements to 0
        }
    }
};

```
